SELECT m.id, 'Airflow Diagram', 'airflow-diagram', '<h2>Airflow Diagram</h2>
<p>Check out this short video explaining the desiccant dehumidifier airflow process.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Embedded YouTube video — "Demystifying Desiccant Dehumidification" airflow process explanation — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>An airflow diagram for a desiccant dehumidifier illustrates the key components of the dehumidifier and the <strong>2 opposing airstreams</strong> within it.</p>
<h3>Here are the steps in the airflow process:</h3>
<ol>
<li>First, we have the <strong>Process Inlet</strong>, where untreated air enters the dehumidifier. This air is often outdoor air or process air that requires dehumidification.</li>
<li>Next, we see the <strong>Pre-filtration</strong>. Before entering the main components of the dehumidifier, the air passes through a filter to remove particles, dust, and contaminants from the air stream, protecting downstream components and ensuring clean air enters the system.
<ul><li><em>NOTE: Filter options are available based on the application and level of filtration needed.</em></li></ul>
</li>
<li>An optional component that you might see next is a <strong>Pre-Cooling Coil</strong> in some dehumidifiers, especially in humid climates. The air must pass through a pre-cooling coil. This coil, often chilled-water or direct-expansion, slightly lowers the temperature of the incoming air, also lowering the vapor pressure to help optimize the desiccant''s moisture removal capability.</li>
<li>Now we move to the heart of our diagram: the <strong>Desiccant Wheel</strong>, often called a <strong>Rotor</strong>. It consists of a substrate material impregnated with a desiccant, such as silica gel. As moist air passes through the wheel, it is <strong>adsorbed</strong> by the desiccant, effectively dehumidifying the air. Once the air is dehumidified, it is released into the conditioned space through the process outlet.</li>
<li>Let''s take a look at the <strong>Reactivation Air</strong> stream in our flow diagram. In this section of the regeneration process, a stream of air is used to remove the accumulated moisture from the desiccant wheel. The regenerated air is typically exhausted to the outdoors or to another part of the system, allowing the desiccant wheel to continue operating effectively.</li>
</ol>', 1, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'What is a Desiccant?', 'what-is-a-desiccant', '<h2>What is a Desiccant?</h2>
<p>Desiccants are a group of materials that have a high affinity for moisture. They are hygroscopic and tend to maintain a state of dryness (removing moisture under vapor from the air to create an environment that is moisture-free environments).</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Embedded YouTube video — "Demystifying Desiccant Dehumidification" explaining what a desiccant is — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>There are two categories of desiccants: <strong>adsorbents</strong> and <strong>absorbents</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Adsorbents</strong> are traditionally used in desiccant dehumidification systems. They can change into a liquid when super-saturated with water. They attract water molecules on their surface. They can exchange capacities when no longer able to hold water.</li>
<li><strong>Absorbents</strong> are physically altered when they take on water. They can include materials that increase in volume without the adsorption process. They showcase moisture removal capacities that may be dependent on liquid-form absorption.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Typical Desiccant Dehumidification Psychrometric Process</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Psychrometric chart showing typical desiccant dehumidification process curve — Moisture Load Removal Equation: 4.5 x CFM x (W-in minus W-out) — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Desiccant-based dehumidification transfers water in its vapor state from the air to the surface of the desiccant. The desiccant due to its surface vapor pressure is lower than the air''s, allowing the desiccant to attract moisture from the air. Moisture is adsorbed before it can transition to a condensed liquid state.</p>
<p>Now the desiccant must be desorbed before it can continue to remove moisture from the air. Reactivation is accomplished by exposing the saturated desiccant to a second airstream at a high temperature so that the surface vapor pressure of the activated desiccant is lower than that of the saturated desiccant, driving the desiccant wheel to begin releasing the accumulated moisture back into this reactivation airstream for exhaust.</p>
<p>In the case of 70% outdoor air systems, some cooling upstream of the desiccant may be needed. The efficiency and effectiveness of the desiccant increases as the inlet air temperature drops, allowing much lower dewpoints to be accomplished.</p>
<p>To determine if pre-cooling is required, the outdoor air humidity and desired space conditions must be taken into account. In more demanding applications, or in environments requiring low dewpoint temperatures, pre-cooling may be necessary. Pre-cooling can be accomplished with either a cooling coil or it may effectively add energy to the process that is not required.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Close-up photograph of silica gel desiccant beads — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 2, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Desiccant vs. Refrigerant-based Systems', 'desiccant-vs-refrigerant-based-systems', '<h2>Desiccant vs. Refrigerant-based Systems</h2>
<p>Check out this short video comparing desiccant dehumidification to refrigerant dehumidification.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Embedded YouTube video — "Demystifying Desiccant Dehumidification" comparing desiccant vs refrigerant-based systems — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<blockquote><p>Dehumidification achieved by the adsorption of water molecules marks an important distinction between desiccant technology and that of refrigerant based air-conditioning.</p></blockquote>
<h3>Desiccant vs. Refrigeration</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Side-by-side comparison diagram — "Desiccant" dehumidification airflow vs. "Refrigeration" (traditional A/C) airflow, showing key process differences — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>In traditional refrigerant-based HVAC systems, a chilled cooling coil condenses water vapor in the air when dehumidification takes place. The temperature of the surrounding atmosphere and the air around the evaporator coils falls below this point. This point (dew point of condensation) is removed from the air by the coils through liquid drainage.</p>
<p>The supply air from such systems is typically much cooler since the energy in the supply air heat energy is transferred to a chiller or condensing unit where it is deposited outside. This requires a mechanical system to move the heat to the outdoors. This approach largely helps cool the room; heat energy is transferred to a chiller or condensing unit, where it is deposited outside via the condensing coils.</p>
<blockquote><p>It is important to understand that traditional refrigerant-based systems like this are designed primarily to cool the air sensibly, with dehumidification being a byproduct.</p></blockquote>
<h3>Reheat Wastes Energy</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Diagram showing reheat energy waste — traditional A/C cools to 49°F then reheats to 57°F, illustrating the energy penalty of over-cooling for dehumidification — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Traditional refrigerant-based HVAC systems quickly absorb (remove) the latent heat of condensation via the cold refrigerant in their evaporating through the coil. In effect, this typically makes the air much colder than it needs to be before the moisture can be removed. The desiccant dehumidifier simply takes the moisture from the environment or releases moisture when not needed.</p>
<p>For some problem situations, applications needing lower indoor humidity levels require the air to be more deeply dehumidified. With traditional refrigerant-based air-conditioning (mechanical cooling), the air is cooled to condensation temperatures below the dew point. Many times, the supply air must be drastically overcooled and then warmed back up via a reheating process to achieve comfort while maintaining the controlled humidity. When energy standards are not on energy-efficient or sustainable option for outdoor emission reductions particularly when this heat is provided by equipment running fossil fuel as an energy source.</p>
<p>By leaving the unconditioned sensible heat in the desiccant''s airstream, it can be utilized as "free-heating" or "free warm addition" component parts that add energy to the process airstream. This is a big sustainability feature in the use of solid desiccant dehumidification systems.</p>
<blockquote><p>REMEMBER: Solid desiccant dehumidification removes water from the air in its molecular state. The desiccant <strong>never</strong> turns moist. This is a benefit for solid desiccant dehumidification as it is <strong>not limited</strong> by cold surfaces which could lead to liquid condensation.</p></blockquote>', 3, TRUE, 5
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
