SELECT m.id, 'The Process Air Stream', 'the-process-air-stream', '<h2>The Process Air Stream</h2>
<blockquote><p>The process airstream of a desiccant dehumidifier undergoes several stages as it moves through a dehumidification system.</p></blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Inlet &amp; Filtration</li>
<li>Pre-Cooling</li>
<li>The Desiccant Wheel</li>
<li>Optional Bypass System</li>
<li>Fan Assembly, and</li>
<li>Discharge</li>
</ol>
<h3>Process Side Components</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Labeled diagram of the process side of a desiccant dehumidifier showing: 1. Process Air Inlet, 2. Process Filter, 3. Pre-Cooling Coil, 4. Desiccant Wheel (Rotor), 5. React Heater, 6. Process Air Fan, 7. React Air Inlet, 8. Process Air Outlet, 9. PLC Touch Screen — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<h3>Here''s a breakdown of the process:</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Inlet and Filtration:</strong> The process airstream typically begins with outdoor air being drawn into the dehumidifier unit. This air may pass through filters to remove particulates and contaminants, ensuring clean air enters the system. Filtration helps protect downstream components, maintains indoor air quality, and can be as stringent as needed, depending on requirements specified by the end user.</li>
<li><strong>Pre-Cooling:</strong> In some configurations, especially in applications where outdoor air is hot and humid, a pre-cooling coil may be installed upstream of the desiccant wheel. This coil, which can be chilled-water or direct-expansion, slightly lowers the temperature of the incoming air. Pre-cooling optimizes the desiccant''s ability to remove moisture by reducing the air temperature and thus lowering its vapor pressure.</li>
<li>The desiccant wheel is impregnated with a substrate material as we can also go to the most process air passes through the wheel, water molecules are adsorbed by the desiccant, effectively removing moisture.</li>
<li><strong>Optional Bypass System:</strong> Some systems feature a bypass duct and damper below the desiccant wheel. This allows for the blending of conditioned air from the wheel with unconditioned air, enabling precise control over the final air mixture and environmental conditions.</li>
<li><strong>Fan Assembly:</strong> After passing through the desiccant wheel (and potentially the bypass system), the dehumidified air is propelled by a fan assembly. This fan ensures proper airflow and distribution throughout the system and into the conditioned space.</li>
<li><strong>Discharge:</strong> Finally, the dehumidified air is discharged from the unit into field-supplied ductwork, which distributes the conditioned air to the conditioned space. The air leaving the desiccant dehumidifier is deeply dehumidified and may be slightly warmed due to the <strong>latent heat of adsorption</strong>, a result of moisture removal.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>Throughout the process airstream, the desiccant dehumidifier efficiently removes moisture from the air, contributing to improved indoor air quality, comfort, and support of various industrial manufacturing processes where precise humidity control is essential.</p></blockquote>
<blockquote><p>Pre-cooling is sometimes necessary as a method to lower the temperature of the process air prior to entering the wheel.</p></blockquote>', 5, TRUE, 5
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'What is a Rotor?', 'what-is-a-rotor', '<h2>What is a Rotor?</h2>
<p>Our next component is the desiccant wheel...</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Humorous "No, not a hamster wheel" image — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Humorous "Not a ferris wheel" image — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Humorous "and not the Showcase Showdown wheel" image — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p><strong>The DESICCANT WHEEL</strong> — also called a <strong>rotor</strong>.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Photograph of a large desiccant wheel (rotor) installed in a dehumidifier unit, showing the rotating honeycomb matrix structure — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>The rotor number of substrate is primarily made of fiberglass, aluminum, or ceramic, which is impregnated with silica gel (our desiccant). As moist air flows through the rotor, water molecules stick to the surface of the desiccant. To avoid liquid condensation, air passes through the wheel as a continuous process of air flow that no liquid process forms when the moisture molecules hold tight to our silica gel.</p>
<p>As hot reactivation air passes through the opposing section of the wheel, the moisture is driven off and exits the system. This is why no liquid drainage is needed. As the wheel spins, fresh, dry desiccant material is continuously brought back into the process airstream for more moisture pickup, making the dehumidification process continuous.</p>
<p>The warming of the air as it exits the desiccant wheel can be higher than the inlet of the air at a higher temperature than that of the process air. This is at a measured or referenced difference between desiccant and refrigerant-cooled dehumidifiers. The air leaving the desiccant wheel may be at a higher temperature than the ambient air, and may be slightly warmed due to the <strong>latent heat of adsorption</strong>, a result of moisture removal.</p>
<h3>Side View of Desiccant Wheel (Rotor)</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Side view photograph of desiccant wheel rotor showing the flat disc profile — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<h3>Front View of Desiccant Wheel with Clean Airflow Intake Unit</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Front view photograph of desiccant wheel showing the honeycomb cell structure face — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Sometimes a small <strong>bypass duct and damper</strong> are located directly before the wheel. This can be used to blend or mixing of fresh unconditioned air and so can mix in a way that reduces environmental part of the indoor space, enabling the unit to maintain precise dew points down to temperatures that create conditions at or below humidity levels.</p>
<p>More rarely the process enters a face assembly and is discharged through the end of the unit into the field-supplied ductwork that distributes the conditioned air to the conditioned space. At this point, options might include pre-heating, post-heating, post-cooling, UV lights, chemical misting that adds filtration, humidification, or anything that is client required.</p>', 6, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Understanding the Reactivation Process', 'understanding-the-reactivation-process', '<h2>Understanding the Reactivation Process</h2>
<blockquote><p>The reactivation air quantity is a smaller fraction of the total wheel air flow, typically between 25% and 33%.</p></blockquote>
<p>This air may come from the outdoors or from some other source of clean air. It then enters the reactivation side. Before entering the desiccant wheel, it is heated to a specified temperature and then enters at a specified temperature.</p>
<p>Adding thermal energy heats the desiccant, increasing its surface vapor pressure so it is now higher than the vapor pressure of the reactivation air in the wheel. This allows the adsorbed water molecules held tightly in the wheel to break their bond with the silica gel and be removed. This process is known as <em>desorption</em>.</p>
<p>The reactivation airstream may be heated to somewhere between 200°F to 250°F depending on the application. The exhaust from the reactivation side of the process air may be directed to exhaust from the process air fan.</p>
<p>The thermal energy required for reactivation can come from various sources including <strong>gas, electricity, steam, or waste heat</strong>. If waste heat is available, it can significantly lower the cost to operate.</p>
<p>From here the reactivation air exits the regeneration coil on to be collected by an <strong>aftercooled</strong> airstream. The air at this point has been slightly cooled before it enters the wheel. The wheel is in fact loaded with moisture and is in a very high-temperature, high-desiccant state. The air is loaded with moisture and is in at or extremely high-temperature state. The more the desiccant goes through the reactivation process, the more moisture will be removed from the wheel and released to the outdoors.</p>
<h3>Reactivation Air Flow Diagram</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Labeled flow diagram showing reactivation airside components in sequence: React Air In → React Filter &amp; Heater → React Coil → React Fan → React Air Out — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 7, TRUE, 5
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Desiccant Dehumidifier Unit Components', 'desiccant-dehumidifier-unit-components', '<h2>Desiccant Dehumidifier Unit Components</h2>
<blockquote><p>The heart of a solid desiccant dehumidifier is its desiccant wheel (or rotor) which is centered between two opposing and isolated air streams.</p></blockquote>
<p>The process airstream consists of the air which is to be dehumidified, and the reactivation airstream removes the moisture which has been adsorbed from the flow desiccant during the dehumidification process. It is the desiccant which "drives" the wheel and allows for a consistent, continuous, and uninterrupted dehumidification process.</p>
<p><strong>Process = Air Dehumidification</strong><br>
<strong>React = Rotor Regeneration</strong></p>
<h3>Flow Diagram</h3>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Complete unit flow diagram showing the full desiccant dehumidifier process with labeled airstreams — process side entering the desiccant wheel and reactivation side regenerating the wheel — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>As mentioned, the dehumidification process is continuous, so if:</p>
<ul>
<li>the wheel is turning,</li>
<li>the heater is functional, and</li>
<li>the fans are moving air,</li>
<li>dehumidification is taking place.</li>
</ul>', 8, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Sustainability and Efficiency', 'sustainability-and-efficiency', '<h2>Sustainability and Efficiency</h2>
<p>Check out this short video on sustainable energy using heat recovery in desiccant dehumidification.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Embedded YouTube video — "Demystifying Desiccant Dehumidification" covering sustainable energy and heat recovery — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Desiccant dehumidification stands out for its sustainability and efficiency, offering energy-efficient solutions for indoor air quality management. By utilizing thermal energy in the adsorption process, desiccant dehumidifiers can reduce energy consumption and simplify processes, making them a sustainable choice for various applications.</p>
<h3>Desiccant dehumidifiers are often regarded as sustainable and energy-efficient solutions for humidity control due to several key factors:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Energy Recovery</li>
<li>No liquid condensation</li>
<li>Adaptive control</li>
<li>Operational flexibility</li>
<li>Reduced refrigerant use</li>
<li>Longevity and durability</li>
</ol>
<h3>Let''s take a closer look at each of these factors:</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Energy Recovery:</strong> Desiccant dehumidifiers utilize the principle of energy recovery during the dehumidification process. Unlike refrigerant-based systems that rely solely on cooling coil condensing and reheating processes, desiccant dehumidifiers recover the heat energy removed from the system or transferred during dehumidification. This heat can be utilized within the system or transferred elsewhere, reducing overall energy consumption.</li>
<li><strong>No Liquid Condensation:</strong> Unlike refrigerant-based systems that rely on condensation units that may generate liquid condensate, desiccant dehumidifiers operate without producing liquid waste. This eliminates the need for drainage systems and reduces the risk of microbial growth associated with standing water, contributing to a cleaner and more sustainable operation.</li>
<li><strong>Adaptive Control:</strong> Desiccant dehumidifiers often incorporate adaptive control systems that adjust their operation based on external conditions and requirements. These systems adapt to changing environmental conditions, delivering consistent indoor dehumidification performance. They can be effectively dehumidified within a wide range of temperatures and environmental conditions. This adaptive operational flexibility makes them suitable for a wide range of temperature and environmental conditions. They can effectively dehumidify within a range of temperatures, making them more energy efficient compared to traditional refrigerant-based systems which might struggle to remove moisture in low-temperature environments requiring low dewpoint levels.</li>
<li><strong>Reduced Refrigerant Use:</strong> Unlike refrigerant-based systems that rely on refrigerants for the dehumidification process, desiccant systems do not rely on refrigerants for the dehumidification process. This eliminates the environmental impact associated with refrigerant leaks, reducing the risk of ozone depletion and global warming potential.</li>
<li><strong>Longevity and Durability:</strong> Desiccant dehumidifiers are often constructed with durable materials and components, leading to longer service life and reduced maintenance requirements. Their robust design contributes to sustainability by minimizing the need for frequent replacements and reducing waste generation.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>Desiccant dehumidifiers offer sustainable and energy-efficient solutions for humidity control through energy recovery, adaptive control systems, operational flexibility, reduced refrigerant use, and longevity. These features make them environmentally friendly choices for various applications, ranging from industrial processes to commercial settings.</p></blockquote>', 9, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Factors that Affect Dehumidification Loads and Calculations', 'factors-affecting-dehumidification-loads-and-calculations', '<h2>Factors that Affect Dehumidification Loads and Calculations</h2>
<p>Understanding the influence of various factors that directly impact desiccant dehumidification calculations and unit specifications is crucial when designing an effective desiccant dehumidification system.</p>
<p>These factors include but are not limited to:</p>
<ol>
<li>Outdoor Climate</li>
<li>Number of openings in the space</li>
<li>Occupancy level</li>
<li>Occupant workload</li>
<li>Types of materials present in the space</li>
</ol>
<h3>Let''s take a closer look at each of these:</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Outdoor climate</strong> plays a vital role in psychrometric calculations for a desiccant dehumidifier. In humid regions, the air contains more moisture, necessitating a higher dehumidification capacity to achieve desired humidity levels indoors.</li>
<li>The number of <strong>openings</strong> in a space is a significant factor that must be taken into consideration when determining dehumidification loads and temperatures where dew points and humidity levels change through respiration and perspiration. More occupants generally means higher moisture generation, demanding a greater dehumidification capacity.</li>
<li>Additionally, the <strong>workload</strong> of individuals within a space can intensify moisture production. Higher levels of physical activity result in increased perspiration and breathing rate, contributing to higher moisture generation.</li>
<li>Consideration must also be given to the types of <strong>materials</strong> present. Certain products, furniture, and chemicals emit various organic compounds, or VOCs, at different humidity levels, which can affect indoor air quality and product integrity, and moisture, necessitating specialized dehumidification strategies to maintain air quality and prevent moisture-related damage.</li>
</ol>
<p>From outdoor climate to human activity and material composition, these factors seriously influence dehumidification calculations. By assessing these variables, we can engineer solutions that effectively manage humidity levels, ensuring comfort, and preserving the integrity of the indoor environment.</p>', 10, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Common Applications for Desiccant Dehumidification', 'common-applications-for-desiccant-dehumidification', '<h2>Common Applications for Desiccant Dehumidification</h2>
<p>There are many common applications where the use of a desiccant dehumidifier plays a critical role in maintaining optimal conditions. These conditions can be required by regulatory bodies, they might be necessary for optimal product manufacturing, or they may simply produce a more comfortable indoor environment for its occupants.</p>
<p>One of the most common applications is in <strong>food processing facilities</strong>. Low humidity environments prevent moisture buildup, preserving the quality and shelf life of products while inhibiting the growth of mold and bacteria. Think about a sugar or salt factory — how about potato chip producing facilities. Even the smallest about of moisture can ruin product quality or lead to product contamination.</p>
<p>Similarly, <strong>pharmaceutical manufacturing</strong> relies on precise humidity control to ensure drug potency and stability. These environments must adhere to strict hygiene and regulatory standards, making low humidity levels which must meet strict compliance regulations. These environments must adhere to strict compliance regulations. They might simply produce a more comfortable indoor environment for their occupants.</p>
<p>In <strong>warehouses and storage facilities</strong>, low desiccant dehumidification, by reducing high humidity, creates better warehousing conditions. Low humidity helps to prevent the deterioration of stored items due to moisture, mold and corrosion. Desiccant dehumidification systems help create optimal storage conditions.</p>
<p>While these are some of the most prevalent applications, desiccant dehumidification solutions can be provided to environments not listed above.</p>
<p>For instance, in <strong>museums and art galleries</strong>, managing relative humidity is critical for preserving cultural heritage. Long-term, even small changes in humidity can cause irreversible damage to sensitive artifacts, paintings, and historical documents. By regulating humidity levels, desiccant dehumidification protects these items and maintains the integrity of cultural and historical items.</p>
<p>In <strong>agricultural</strong> settings, such as greenhouses, desiccant dehumidification can optimize growth conditions for plants while minimizing the risk of fungal diseases. By regulating humidity levels, growers can create optimal conditions for plant growth.</p>
<p>Learn more about different applications for our desiccant dehumidifiers by watching our YouTube Playlist here.</p>', 11, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Conclusion', 'conclusion', '<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Throughout this course, we''ve learned about various aspects of desiccant dehumidifiers and the processes that allow us to enrich the lives of our customers by helping them achieve a conditioned space that meets their specific humidity control needs.</p>
<h3>In this course, we learned:</h3>
<ol>
<li>A desiccant dehumidifier removes water vapor from the air by means of a desiccant.</li>
<li>A desiccant is not inhibited by the physical properties of water because it holds water vapor without creating condensation.</li>
<li>Refrigerant-based systems are designed to cool the air, with dehumidification being a byproduct.</li>
<li>Desiccant dehumidification can be more efficient and economical than refrigeration-based dehumidifiers at lower temperatures and reduced moisture levels.</li>
<li>Desiccant dehumidification can produce extremely low leaving air dew-point temperatures, perhaps as low as -80°F, or to maintain environments at single-digit relative humidities, if required.</li>
<li>A rotor is comprised of our desiccant and can accommodate airflow rates from 75 to 30,000 CFM.</li>
<li>A standard desiccant dehumidifier consists of a filter, process and react fans, a heater and a rotor.</li>
<li>There is a multitude of industries that utilize desiccant dehumidification, and desiccant systems can be highly efficient.</li>
<li>The dehumidification process always functions continuously, so dehumidification can be sustained continuously.</li>
<li>There is a multitude of industries that utilize desiccant dehumidification, and desiccant systems are continually and energy efficient.</li>
<li>There is a multitude of industries that utilize desiccant dehumidification, and desiccant systems are continuously and sustainably efficient.</li>
</ol>
<p>Perhaps somewhere in the past you may have had no reason to believe that solid desiccant dehumidification is particularly overly confusing or ineffective, costly, expensive, and should only be applied in certain situations. We hope this course has put these ideas to rest.</p>
<blockquote><p>We have shown that solid desiccant dehumidification is an energy-efficient, sustainable, and cost-effective solution for almost any environment requiring the ultimate goal of dehumidification. Innovative Air Technologies desiccant dehumidifiers deliver when properly applied.</p></blockquote>', 12, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'dessicant-dehumidification-training'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;

