SELECT m.id, 'Glossary of Terms', 'glossary-of-terms', '<h2>Glossary of Terms</h2><h3>General Terminology</h3><p><em>Core business, software, and operational terms used across the organization.</em></p><p><strong>AI (Artificial Intelligence)</strong><br>Machine-based intelligence that learns from data and adapts to perform human-like tasks.</p><p><strong>API (Application Program Interface)</strong><br>Allows different software systems to communicate and sync data, reducing duplicate entry.</p><p><strong>BACnet (Building Automation &amp; Control Network)</strong><br>Open-source communication protocol used in HVAC systems for device integration.</p><p><strong>B.O.M (Bill of Materials)</strong><br>Centralized list of all components and instructions required to manufacture a product.</p><p><strong>CFM (Cubic Feet per Minute)</strong><br>Measurement of airflow volume.</p><p><strong>CRM (Customer Records Manager)</strong><br>Web-based system storing customer data (purchases, warranties, service history, etc.). Integrates with ERP systems.</p><p><strong>Client Portal</strong><br>Customer-facing CRM feature providing access to system data, invoices, warranties, and maintenance reminders.</p><p><strong>ERP (MIE TRAK)</strong><br>Enterprise Resource Planning system used to manage manufacturing workflows from start to finish.</p><p><strong>RFQ (Request for Quote)</strong><br>Document used to request pricing for products or services.</p><h3>Dehumidification &amp; HVAC Concepts</h3><p><em>Fundamental principles that explain how moisture, air, and temperature interact.</em></p><p><strong>Dew Point (DP)</strong><br>Temperature at which air becomes saturated and moisture begins to condense.</p><p><strong>Relative Humidity (RH)</strong><br>Percentage of moisture in the air relative to its maximum capacity.</p><p><strong>Dry-Bulb Temperature</strong><br>Ambient air temperature measured by a standard thermometer.</p><p><strong>Wet-Bulb Temperature (WBT)</strong><br>Temperature measured with a moistened sensor; reflects heat + humidity combined.</p><p><strong>Desiccant</strong><br>Material (silica gel in IAT systems) used to absorb moisture from air.</p><p><strong>Psychrometric Chart</strong><br>Tool used to visualize and calculate air properties and thermodynamic processes.</p><h3>IAT Product Lines</h3><p><em>Overview of the different dehumidification systems offered by IAT and their applications.</em></p><p><strong>Compact Units</strong><br>Small industrial dehumidifiers (75–600 CFM).</p><p><strong>Portable Series</strong><br>Customizable portable units (75–10,000 CFM).</p><p><strong>Rotor Series</strong><br>Large, flagship systems (600–30,000 CFM) for demanding applications.</p><p><strong>IDP (Integrated Dehumidification Package)</strong><br>Complete air treatment system handling both temperature and humidity (50–30,000 CFM).</p><h3>System Components &amp; Operation</h3><p><em>Key mechanical components and how IAT systems remove moisture from the air.</em></p><p><strong>Rotor Units</strong><br>Desiccant wheel system with two air streams:</p><ul><li><strong>Process Air</strong>: Air being dried</li><li><strong>Reactivation Air</strong>: Heated air used to remove moisture from the rotor</li></ul><p><strong>Reactivation Heater</strong><br>Heats air (typically 270–310°F) to dry the desiccant rotor.</p><p><strong>Reactivation Types</strong><br>Heat source options:</p><ul><li>Electric</li><li>Gas</li><li>Steam</li><li>Hot Water</li></ul><p><strong>React Fan</strong><br>Exhausts moisture-laden air outside the building.</p><p><strong>Condenser Unit</strong><br>Transfers heat using refrigerant to regulate temperature.</p><h3>Controls &amp; Electrical Components</h3><p><em>Devices and systems responsible for monitoring, controlling, and protecting equipment performance.</em></p><p><strong>iControl PLC (Programmable Logic Controller)</strong><br>Industrial control system that monitors performance and controls system operation.</p><p><strong>VFD (Variable Frequency Drive)</strong><br>Controls motor speed by adjusting power frequency and voltage.</p><p><strong>Humidistat (Hygrostat)</strong><br>Device that measures and controls humidity levels.</p><p><strong>Magnahelic Gauge</strong><br>Measures pressure within the system.</p><p><strong>MERV Rating</strong><br>Indicates filter efficiency (0.3–10 microns).</p><p><strong>RPH (Revolutions per Hour)</strong><br>Speed measurement of the rotor.</p><h3>Software &amp; Internal Systems</h3><p><em>Internal tools and platforms used to support sales, monitoring, and customer engagement.</em></p><p><strong>DryWare</strong><br>Internal sales software containing product and customer data.</p><p><strong>Dry AI / Tara</strong><br>Remote monitoring and alarm system (primarily for rotor units).</p><p><strong>Dry Guard</strong><br>Automated maintenance notification system (in development).</p><h3>Documentation &amp; Standards</h3><p><em>Standardized documents and classifications used to guide production, installation, and system identification.</em></p><p><strong>I.O.M (Installation, Operation &amp; Maintenance)</strong><br>Guidelines for system setup, operation, and upkeep.</p><p><strong>Nominal CFM Range</strong><br>Standard airflow capacities: 75–30,000 CFM.</p><p><strong>System Types</strong></p><ul><li>R: Rotor</li><li>D: Drum (obsolete)</li><li>B: Bed (obsolete)</li><li>AHU: Air Handling Unit (obsolete)</li></ul><h3>IAT Control System Features</h3><p><em>Standard control components and safety features built into IAT systems.</em></p><p><strong>On-Off-Auto Switch</strong></p><ul><li><strong>On</strong>: Manual operation</li><li><strong>Auto</strong>: Controlled by humidistat</li><li>Includes pilot lights for status indication</li></ul><p><strong>Temperature Control (Electric Reactivation)</strong></p><ul><li>Maintains reactivation temperature (250–300°F typical)</li></ul><p><strong>Variable Frequency Drives (VFDs)</strong></p><ul><li>Adjust and maintain airflow without manual dampers</li></ul><p><strong>Reactivation Burner Controller</strong></p><ul><li>Controls gas burner output via 0–10V signal</li></ul><p><strong>Motor Starter Protectors</strong></p><ul><li>Protect motors based on full load amperage</li></ul><p><strong>Contactors</strong></p><ul><li>Manage staged electric heater control</li></ul><p><strong>SCR (Silicone Controlled Rectifier)</strong></p><ul><li>Provides precise control of heater power</li></ul><p><strong>Sensors</strong></p><ul><li>Monitor temperature and humidity throughout the system</li></ul><p><strong>Relays</strong></p><ul><li>Control individual electrical components (plug-and-play)</li></ul><p><strong>Safety Systems</strong></p><ul><li>High temperature protection</li><li>Airflow monitoring</li><li>Current protection</li><li>Cool-down timers (fans run until &lt;120°F)</li></ul>', 4, TRUE, 5
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
